##DESCRIPTION
##KEYWORDS('factoring', 'identities')
##DIFFICULTY('hard')
##  Factoring a perfect square trinomial with 2 variables 
##
## Author:  Mark Schmitt
## Date:    2001/02 School Year
## Course:  Algebra 2 (Honors or Regular)
##
##ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

TEXT(beginproblem());

$A = random(1,9,1);
$B = non_zero_random(-9,9,1);
while (gcd($A,$B) > 1) {$B = random(1,9,1);}

$C = random(1,9,1);
$D = random(1,9,1);
while (gcd($C,$D)>1) {$D = random(1,9,1);}

$c1 = $A**2;
$c2 = $B**2;
$e1 = $C*2;
$e2 = $D*2;
$c3 = 2*$A*$B;

BEGIN_TEXT

The polynomial \($c1 x^{$e1} +$c3 x^{$C} y^{$D} + $c2 y^{$e2} \) 
can be factored into
the product of two polynomials, \(A \cdot B\) where the 
coefficient of y in \(A\) is
greater than or equal to the coefficient of y in \(B\).  Find \(A\) and \(B\).
$BR
$BR
\(A = \) \{ans_rule(10)\}
$BR
\(B = \) \{ans_rule(10)\}

END_TEXT

$ans1 = "$A*x**$C + $B*y**$D";
$ans2 = "$A*x**$C + $B*y**$D";

ANS(fun_cmp ($ans1,var=>['x','y']));
ANS(fun_cmp ($ans2,var=>['x','y']));

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.;

